{
  "answer": "In Allama Iqbal's poem *Ek Makra aur Makhi* (from *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, ch. 20), the spider—having failed with a direct invitation—resorts to flattery to lure the fly into its web.[^1]\n\n> The spider thought, “She's clever, I can tell.  \n> How can I trap this wretch within my cell?  \n> But flattery can make a hundred schemes succeed,  \n> The world is slave to flattery's own creed.”  \n> And so he told the fly, “My dear lady,  \n> God has bestowed on you great dignity.  \n> Whoever sees your face is filled with love,  \n> A single glance is more than quite enough.  \n> Your eyes are like two diamonds, shining bright,  \n> Your head, God crowned with a plume of light.  \n> This grace, this dress, this beauty, and this art!  \n> And then your song in flight that steals the heart!”[^1]\n\nThe fly, softened by these words, then approaches and is caught.[^2]\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, ch. 20 \"Ek Makra aur Makhi\" (translation), [paragraphs](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/20-ek-makra-aur-makhi/translation/#p-7d0fa0).\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, ch. 20 \"Ek Makra aur Makhi\" (translation), [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/20-ek-makra-aur-makhi/translation/#p-047eb6).",
